00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:29.970
is really central. We can address
questions like where and when these new

00:03:29.970 --> 00:03:36.610
gene mutations happen that give us
different skin color in this case,

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:41.570
potentially improved diagnostic and
treatments, test different kinds of

00:03:41.570 --> 00:03:47.490
molecular hypotheses and finally predict
trait values. This could be useful in a

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:52.450
forensic context when the person's not
there, you don't have any information

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:58.620
about who he is, to make some predictions
as well as in Epidemiology. Skin is

00:03:58.620 --> 00:04:04.860
mediating something about the disease
condition. We know it's really critical in

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:10.120
producing enough Vitamin D.
We can measure the skin from the DNA

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:16.640
alone, so not having measured it in the
person. So there's a lot of potential

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:23.210
there. Here's an example of a melanocyte
and keratinocytes, typically they reach up

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:29.110
to 30 or 40 keratinocytes and pass off
melanosomes. So it's just a little bit

00:04:29.110 --> 00:04:34.560
about the biology. We know a lot about the
genes that are forming these melanosomes

00:04:34.560 --> 00:04:40.490
and controlling their transfer up to the
keratinocytes. I've always been fascinated

00:04:40.490 --> 00:04:47.750
by human variation and here's a slide of
18 young women who we collected recently

00:04:47.750 --> 00:04:54.210
as part of our sampling. You can get
quickly a sense of the diversity of human

00:04:54.210 --> 00:05:03.200
pigmentation; skin, hair, and eyes from
this. We can look at more detailed

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:08.970
descriptions, quantitative descriptions.
This is a histogram showing the

00:05:08.970 --> 00:05:14.520
pigmentation levels measured in three
populations. The one on the far left is

00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:19.990
European-American sample from State
College, the black bars to the right are

00:05:19.990 --> 00:05:27.590
African-Americans from Washington DC, and
then a sample of African-Caribbeans from

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:32.270
England. The African-Caribbeans are
shifted over to the right a little bit

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:39.170
compared to the African-Americans and
that's darker skin. In fact they have less

00:05:39.170 --> 00:05:45.930
European ancestry, less European admixture
than the African-Americans do; about 10%

00:05:45.930 --> 00:05:51.460
compared to 20%. So there's a strong
relationship there between your recent

00:05:51.460 --> 00:05:58.370
admixture and your skin color. We do see
too, this red bar here shows the extent of

00:05:58.370 --> 00:06:06.070
overlap because this slide also emphasizes
how our observation of each other is

00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:10.860
substantially biased.
Sociologists have studied this in detail

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:15.500
and light skinned people see dark skin
people as darker than they are. Dark

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:19.990
skinned people see light skinned people as
lighter than they are. So you can't really

00:06:19.990 --> 00:06:26.240
rely on your perceptions or at least it's
worth looking inward to see what effect

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:33.720
that may have on how you see those around
you. We know the environment has been a

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:38.440
major factor in the evolution of skin
color. That green line there is the

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:45.610
equator and latitude or the distance north
and south of the equator have a major

00:06:45.610 --> 00:06:51.610
effect on skin color. We know from more
detailed analyses that it's actually the

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:56.650
ultraviolet radiation at ground level that
really has the strongest effect on skin

00:06:56.650 --> 00:07:03.390
color. So our skin is tied to the
environment and we can propose or discuss

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:09.030
the different mechanisms that may be
controlling this response. I think the

00:07:09.030 --> 00:07:15.620
strongest evidence is for lightning of
skin due to the need to produce Vitamin D.

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:22.760
A very few natural sources that we can
dietarily consume enough Vitamin D to keep

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:27.450
us healthy, but our skin can produce
Vitamin D. So with ultraviolet light

00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:32.490
hitting your skin, you can produce Vitamin
D if your skin's light enough for that

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:37.410
environment and if you're exposed enough,
if you have enough skin showing and if you

00:07:37.410 --> 00:07:44.280
spend enough time outdoors. So lots of
conditions on being healthy through

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:49.190
getting your Vitamin D from your skin.
Potentially immune suppression is also

00:07:49.190 --> 00:07:55.370
something that is good in certain
instances. Darker skin probably evolved to

00:07:55.370 --> 00:08:00.850
protect us from sunburn, skin cancer,
protect us from too much immune

00:08:00.850 --> 00:08:08.970
suppression and also perhaps to mediate
folic acid photolysis to protect our folic

00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:13.480
acid stores from being destroyed.
Ultraviolet light helps to create Vitamin

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:21.150
D, but it also destroys folic acid.
Finally, both low and high pigmentation

00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:26.500
can be mediated through sexual selection
and also the relaxation of selection as

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:32.840
population move from one area to another
area. We can talk about the average

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:40.850
history of individuals, persons and
populations. And this tree shows... I know

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:46.780
it's kind of complex but that's really the
best representation that we can make of

00:08:46.780 --> 00:08:52.610
our history. Although this is about 10
years old, I think it still holds in most

00:08:52.610 --> 00:08:58.130
of the major branches here. And it's not
only a branching through the fission,

00:08:58.130 --> 00:09:03.400
separation of populations, but also the
fusion of populations. You can see here

00:09:03.400 --> 00:09:08.000
how we have drawn these little branches
here to illustrate admixture or the

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:14.320
movement of people to join other
populations. Our species really has much

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:20.920
more of a wisteria vine history when
branches cross they fuse and they join

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:26.180
again making new populations as opposed to
any kind of tree or bush pattern. That is

00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:31.830
an average pattern. Evolution really
doesn't happen...at least a lot of

00:09:31.830 --> 00:09:37.930
evolution, the adaptive evolution, happens
more on a gene by gene basis. So it's

00:09:37.930 --> 00:09:44.460
modular, each gene has its own history.
The genes that cause differences among us

00:09:44.460 --> 00:09:48.920
today are genes that have very recent
evolutionary histories and have been very

00:09:48.920 --> 00:09:57.620
actively evolving in the past 75,000
years, say, since human populations had

00:09:57.620 --> 00:10:03.380
their common origin in Africa. Many
populations stayed in Africa, some small

00:10:03.380 --> 00:10:08.830
set of populations moved out of Africa.
We have tools that let us study how

00:10:08.830 --> 00:10:15.880
these...tracking the molecular evolution
of these genes and how quickly they

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:21.910
evolved showing clear evidence that they
have evolved recently or changed frequency

00:10:21.910 --> 00:10:27.280
recently. So these are very valuable
tools. I'll show you an application of one

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:32.390
of those methods in a minute. But I want
to focus really on just three populations

00:10:32.390 --> 00:10:37.020
to start with. These aren't the three most
important populations or three central

00:10:37.020 --> 00:10:42.220
populations. That tree I showed you before
is really a better sampling of human

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:47.090
diversity, but these are worth looking at.
We were initially very light skinned

00:10:47.090 --> 00:10:51.800
before we lost our fur, all mammals are.
You spread your cat's fur, even if it's a

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:57.080
black cat, you'll see the skin is white
underneath. As we lost our fur, changed

00:10:57.080 --> 00:11:01.960
our habits, we needed to become dark
skinned. There's other branches here, the

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:08.000
second branch is a common branch to East
Asians and Europeans. The third branch

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.700
there would contain skin lightening events
that were specific to East Asians, the

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:18.880
fourth branch is the branch specific to
European changes. Finally, additional skin

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:23.210
darkening events possibly on that fifth
branch that I show in this tree. So I

00:11:23.210 --> 00:11:28.720
mentioned admixture mapping before and
this is really a fundamental tool for

00:11:28.720 --> 00:11:34.550
finding genes that cause differences
between populations. Most of the genes are

00:11:34.550 --> 00:11:39.300
the same across all populations. If you
look at the frequencies of alleles across

00:11:39.300 --> 00:11:45.780
populations, about 95% of the total
variation is in common. We have this very

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:50.970
recent common history, but for certain
things, especially superficial aspects,

00:11:50.970 --> 00:11:57.080
superficial traits, we have evolved very
quickly and we can map those kinds of

00:11:57.080 --> 00:12:02.080
genes with this approach. So we basically
start out with two parents; one light skin

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:07.420
and one dark skin. These are the
histograms describing their distributions.

00:12:07.420 --> 00:12:13.570
When they mate, you have the first admixed
generation and there is much less

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:18.410
variation in skin color here or whatever
trait it is that you're talking about.

00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:24.360
Everybody has two copies, two genomes; one
from European ancestor and one from an

00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:29.100
African ancestor in this case. But by the
second generation and all the generations

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:33.680
afterwards, you have a lot of variation. A
lot of phenotypic variation and these are

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:39.790
ideal samples for discovering which are
the genes that are affecting this trait.

00:12:39.790 --> 00:12:45.950
Here it is as a chromosomal view. So you
have two European chromosomes, two African

00:12:45.950 --> 00:12:50.650
chromosomes or one of each. You get one of
each by having one parent from each

00:12:50.650 --> 00:12:56.390
population. These black bars are
recombination points so you don't pass on

00:12:56.390 --> 00:13:00.380
to your kids the same chromosomes you got
from your parents. You mix them up and

00:13:00.380 --> 00:13:07.260
then pass on this mixed up set of
chromosomes to your kids. And after a few

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:11.360
generations, you end up with these
chimeric chromosomes that have different

00:13:11.360 --> 00:13:16.310
ancestry segments. We can track those
ancestry segments and use that information

00:13:16.310 --> 00:13:24.100
to map genes. We do need to be careful
about stratification. So there's variation

00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:29.900
in admixture levels across population.
This slide here shows you how the

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:34.550
proportion of West African ancestry is
positively correlated with the skin color

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:40.160
measure, the M index. You see a positive
correlation, you also see the variance is

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:44.420
different so there is a lot more
dispersion here, a lot more variability.

00:13:44.420 --> 00:13:50.510
This is because like most traits, skin
color is much more variable in Africa.

00:13:50.510 --> 00:13:55.210
Even just considering the subset of
Africa, West Africa where the enslaved

00:13:55.210 --> 00:14:00.380
ancestors of the African-Americans and
Brazilians and other populations that are

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:06.240
represented here were derived. So even at
that subset of Africa is much more

00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:10.550
variable than Europe.
But you have this confounding. So you have

00:14:10.550 --> 00:14:16.460
to deal with the fact that ancestry is
going to be correlated with any...our skin

00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:20.590
color will be correlated with any marker
that you measure that's different between

00:14:20.590 --> 00:14:26.170
those parental groups. But you can reduce
that, you can remove that statistically.

00:14:26.170 --> 00:14:30.450
It's a process called conditioning or
controlling. You basically remove the

00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:36.190
effects of one variable to study another.
This is the Duffy null locus, locus of

00:14:36.190 --> 00:14:41.960
very substantially between populations and
you can see the genotype determines the

00:14:41.960 --> 00:14:47.160
distribution of skin color. It has nothing
to do with skin color. When you control

00:14:47.160 --> 00:14:54.230
for the variation and ancestry, you get
rid of that effect on skin color. This is

00:14:54.230 --> 00:15:01.750
the cover of the journal where we
published on the SLC24A5 gene. This gene

00:15:01.750 --> 00:15:08.870
was first discovered by Keith Cheng as the
golden gene for zebra fish. So it affected

00:15:08.870 --> 00:15:13.210
zebra fish coloration. Keith called me up
and said, "Hey, maybe this affects skin

00:15:13.210 --> 00:15:18.400
color." I was quite skeptical until I
looked at public data set where it showed

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:24.480
a locus where Europeans, the blue dot
here, were totally fixed for an allele.

00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:31.150
You didn't find much in other populations.
That's a very unusual circumstance and

00:15:31.150 --> 00:15:35.700
sure enough it has a very dramatic effect
on skin color. You can see that here even

00:15:35.700 --> 00:15:41.090
after controlling for ancestry, you still
have a strong effect on skin color. And in

00:15:41.090 --> 00:15:48.960
fact in genome-wide admixture mapping we
find SLC24A5 is really the strongest gene

00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:55.040
affecting skin color. You see these other
smaller peaks here. Once you condition for

00:15:55.040 --> 00:16:00.900
the effect of SLC24A5, those genes are
much more prominent. So you can see that

00:16:00.900 --> 00:16:06.170
you can detect those. So this statistical
conditioning is a very common tool and

00:16:06.170 --> 00:16:10.870
very useful.
One of the interesting things we found

00:16:10.870 --> 00:16:16.190
about not only SLC24A5 but some of those
other genes that come up in this gene

00:16:16.190 --> 00:16:23.860
mapping analysis like SLC45A2 or the MATP
gene is that the variation that causes

00:16:23.860 --> 00:16:29.130
Europeans to be light skinned is not the
same as the variation that causes East

00:16:29.130 --> 00:16:35.250
Asians to be light skinned. So this
selective pressure to lighten the skin

00:16:35.250 --> 00:16:40.570
probably in response to migrating to
higher latitudes where there's less UV

00:16:40.570 --> 00:16:46.050
light was quite strong. I mean it seems to
affect any population that moves to a

00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:54.300
higher latitude. This is really kind of
unexpected. We had other hypotheses about

00:16:54.300 --> 00:16:59.320
populations like Melanesians maybe they
shared or didn't share genes with darker

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:06.860
skinned populations, but this is what we
found. And in fact, there are many genes,

00:17:06.860 --> 00:17:11.960
I'm not going to talk to you about many of
these other genes, but I just wanted to

00:17:11.960 --> 00:17:19.930
show you a slide that identified what
we're finding about where these genes

00:17:19.930 --> 00:17:25.250
occur and on which branches they seem to
have evolved. So we're not finding too

00:17:25.250 --> 00:17:30.540
many that are on this common branch of
lightning, in the common population coming

00:17:30.540 --> 00:17:39.470
out of Africa and only a few that are back
as far as on the common branch of all

00:17:39.470 --> 00:17:44.000
human populations. But some of these are
more difficult to study, too. This is

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:49.040
probably the case. I don't think that
those genes don't exist and we can't

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:53.530
understand them, we just haven't been able
to find them yet. One very interesting

00:17:53.530 --> 00:18:00.240
tool we have is to look at the local
genetic diversity. So this is using Short

00:18:00.240 --> 00:18:06.940
Tandem Repeats or STRs. If you watch too
many crime TV shows, you probably already

00:18:06.940 --> 00:18:11.070
know this acronym.
But these are the markers you use for

00:18:11.070 --> 00:18:16.500
identity analysis if you have a forensic
case you type the STR alleles. You can see

00:18:16.500 --> 00:18:22.650
there's lots of different variants. This
is the chromosome here that doesn't have

00:18:22.650 --> 00:18:27.210
the new allele, the A allele, that gives
you a lighter skin. This is the chromosome

00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:31.650
with the lighter skin. So you can see
there is much less variation on that

00:18:31.650 --> 00:18:36.010
chromosome even though it's basically
fixed in Europeans. So there's lots of

00:18:36.010 --> 00:18:39.990
copies of that chromosome which usually
means it's old and you are going to see

00:18:39.990 --> 00:18:44.700
lots of different mutations on it. Lots of
different STR alleles, but you don't. You

00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:50.080
only see pretty much one primary alleles
on most of these. So you can use that

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:56.270
information to date when that mutation
occurred or when it started to change

00:18:56.270 --> 00:19:00.540
frequency. That's really the more
important point is when did that really

00:19:00.540 --> 00:19:07.000
start to evolve. So the dates or the time
is here and the selective coefficient, how

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:13.420
strong the selection was is there, and you
can put these on a tree then. So you can

00:19:13.420 --> 00:19:22.680
look at when the timing of some of these
genes SLC24A5, MATP, and TRP1 changed

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:27.860
frequency compared to when KIT Ligand and
some of the other ones changed frequency.

00:19:27.860 --> 00:19:33.980
And they seem to match those splits on the
tree. So I just want to say we're very

00:19:33.980 --> 00:19:39.570
grateful to all of our volunteers who
participated in these research projects

00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:46.390
and I have lots of other colleagues who
have also helped in getting to this point

00:19:46.390 --> 00:19:50.008
and then several other research labs as
well who are looking into a lot of these

00:19:50.008 --> 00:19:53.991
same questions. Thank you very much.

