00:20:04.614 --> 00:20:10.920
- [Nina] We share with these beautiful
cousins of ours skin that serves a variety

00:20:10.920 --> 00:20:15.440
of important functions, and we've heard a
lot about those functions already today:

00:20:15.440 --> 00:20:20.780
protection, thermoregulation. Today, I'm
going to reprise a little bit of what's

00:20:20.780 --> 00:20:27.270
been said already about the first two
functions, and then talk somewhat about

00:20:27.270 --> 00:20:35.270
this enormous realm of human communication
that we engage in with skin. Over time,

00:20:35.270 --> 00:20:42.220
and through evolution, if we compare the
relative importance of protection and

00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:48.670
thermoregulation versus communication, we
can see that in human evolution,

00:20:48.670 --> 00:20:55.140
communication has become one of the major
functions of skin especially since the

00:20:55.140 --> 00:21:00.820
evolution of functionally naked skin. I
want to first just reprise a little bit

00:21:00.820 --> 00:21:05.130
information about protection, though,
because it's useful to think about what we

00:21:05.130 --> 00:21:13.210
lost. Hair is enormously useful, and our
primate relatives and our mammalian

00:21:13.210 --> 00:21:18.330
ancestors had hair that help to insulate
and protect against all manner of

00:21:18.330 --> 00:21:24.770
environmental problems and abrasion,
ultraviolet radiation and water, and hair

00:21:24.770 --> 00:21:32.730
helps to slow the ingress of pathogens to
the skin. But we lost hair, and although

00:21:32.730 --> 00:21:40.480
there is some controversy about why we
lost it and exactly when, we know that we

00:21:40.480 --> 00:21:48.620
now have functionally naked skin probably
by early Homo times, and almost certainly

00:21:48.620 --> 00:21:55.930
for reasons having to do with the need to
keep cool during exercise by a high volume

00:21:55.930 --> 00:22:01.740
of eccrine sweating. And what the
important conclusion of this is is that

00:22:01.740 --> 00:22:10.640
for much of our...the key portions of our
evolution, hairless bodies are interfaced

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:14.290
with the environment.
A very different situation than in other

00:22:14.290 --> 00:22:21.230
mammals. The evolution of the stratum
corneum, the very top part of the

00:22:21.230 --> 00:22:27.200
epidermis is something that has been dealt
with a lot in the dermatological

00:22:27.200 --> 00:22:33.200
literature. We know that the epidermis,
and particularly the stratum corneum at

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:37.860
the very surface of the epidermis, here,
resists abrasion, restricts water loss,

00:22:37.860 --> 00:22:44.190
and prevents the ingress of pathogens. But
that great change from the haired to the

00:22:44.190 --> 00:22:51.360
hairless condition basically involved
changes to the stratum corneum. So when we

00:22:51.360 --> 00:22:56.980
think about really what Ajit Varki's point
was at the very beginning of this

00:22:56.980 --> 00:23:05.830
symposium, "Why is the skin different." We
see from referring to the chimp genome

00:23:05.830 --> 00:23:15.580
project that in fact, the skin is the most
distinct organ. Human skin has been...has

00:23:15.580 --> 00:23:21.160
many genes that have been evolving
independently, and very different from

00:23:21.160 --> 00:23:28.640
those of chimpanzees much more so than any
organ or cell system. And the most

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:34.950
important genes in this regard are those
having to do with the stratum corneum and

00:23:34.950 --> 00:23:41.460
the barrier functions of the epidermis. We
could go on at length, my colleague, Peter

00:23:41.460 --> 00:23:46.740
Elias has done distinguished work in this
area. We know that this stratum corneum in

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:52.600
humans is particularly lipid-rich that we
have interferon gamma that helps to

00:23:52.600 --> 00:23:57.720
generate a potent antiviral state in the
stratum corneum and that the skin

00:23:57.720 --> 00:24:06.060
microbiome plays an enormously important
and still quite unclear, but emerging

00:24:06.060 --> 00:24:10.200
role.
The skin also has to protect against

00:24:10.200 --> 00:24:15.700
another major assault which is that of the
sun and particularly, ultraviolet

00:24:15.700 --> 00:24:22.680
radiation. We know from data provided from
NASA that the ultraviolet radiation load

00:24:22.680 --> 00:24:28.790
that we get on the Earth's surface is
strongest around the equator shown in the

00:24:28.790 --> 00:24:34.990
bright pink and red tones here in the map.
Much, much lower as we get close to the

00:24:34.990 --> 00:24:40.370
poles, especially in these large land
masses in the northern hemisphere. How

00:24:40.370 --> 00:24:48.410
have humans coped with these high levels
of UV in our ancestral areas, and much

00:24:48.410 --> 00:24:58.350
lower levels in areas of habitation later
in aspects of our evolution? In early

00:24:58.350 --> 00:25:06.500
Homo, the loss of body hair is associated
with the development of permanent, dark

00:25:06.500 --> 00:25:13.200
pigmentation. So instead of having dark
hair covering lightly pigmented skin, we

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:21.490
evolve permanently, darkly pigmented skin.
And that is largely to do with the

00:25:21.490 --> 00:25:28.710
production of high amounts of the
tremendously interesting pigment called

00:25:28.710 --> 00:25:35.810
eumelanin; a fascinating polymer that has
myriad important properties. The most

00:25:35.810 --> 00:25:41.790
important for our purposes being the
ability to scatter and absorb ultraviolet

00:25:41.790 --> 00:25:49.690
radiation and prevent damage to underlying
tissues. Ultraviolet radiation causes a

00:25:49.690 --> 00:25:55.980
lot of damage to the skin that can lead to
skin cancer, especially in individuals who

00:25:55.980 --> 00:26:04.720
are genetically susceptible. But skin
cancer rarely causes mortality.

00:26:04.720 --> 00:26:11.480
So I, as someone who is interested in
figuring out why skin pigmentation evolved

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:16.640
as it did, and specifically why dark
pigmentation evolved, got very interested

00:26:16.640 --> 00:26:22.920
in the effect of ultraviolet radiation on
something that would really count for

00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:30.150
reproductive success in evolution. And I
started looking a lot at folate

00:26:30.150 --> 00:26:36.610
metabolism. Without going into a lot
detail, suffice it to say that we need

00:26:36.610 --> 00:26:43.760
folate, one of the key B vitamins, in
order to fuel DNA synthesis which is

00:26:43.760 --> 00:26:50.380
particularly important in certain parts of
our development in life especially in

00:26:50.380 --> 00:26:56.730
early embryogenesis. When we know that
folate is critical for the formation of

00:26:56.730 --> 00:27:04.480
the embryonic neural tube which is the
precursor of the modern, or the adult,

00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:09.970
nervous system. So, if you have an
environmental agent like ultraviolet

00:27:09.970 --> 00:27:17.530
radiation that can actually break down
folate and affect other aspects of folate

00:27:17.530 --> 00:27:24.140
metabolism in a pregnant mother, then you
can affect reproductive success, and this

00:27:24.140 --> 00:27:30.730
is why we've highlighted that mechanism.
So.here I say the primary, not the only,

00:27:30.730 --> 00:27:36.150
but the primary selective force for the
evolution of permanent dark pigmentation

00:27:36.150 --> 00:27:43.030
is protection against ultraviolet-induced
changes in folate availability and DNA

00:27:43.030 --> 00:27:50.620
synthesis in early embryogenesis and in
sperm production. But humans did not

00:27:50.620 --> 00:27:57.610
remain in the ancestral environment of
Africa. Much of human evolution, including

00:27:57.610 --> 00:28:01.700
much of Homo Sapien's evolution, has
occurred in Africa. Tremendous amounts of

00:28:01.700 --> 00:28:04.270
diversification, but humans have moved
around a lot.

00:28:04.270 --> 00:28:10.310
And here we can see in the history of
modern humans. We have people

00:28:10.310 --> 00:28:16.850
moving...small populations moving out of
Africa into areas of very different

00:28:16.850 --> 00:28:24.120
ultraviolet radiation including very low
areas or very low UV areas later in our

00:28:24.120 --> 00:28:30.150
evolutionary history. Why is that
important? Because ultraviolet radiation,

00:28:30.150 --> 00:28:36.230
mostly a malign influence that we think
about in evolution, is a creative

00:28:36.230 --> 00:28:42.370
influence, and is extremely important in
all vertebrates in the production of

00:28:42.370 --> 00:28:48.480
Vitamin D in the skin. Without
ultraviolet-B radiation we cannot make

00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:55.540
Vitamin D in the skin. And what we have
shown in our research and this has been

00:28:55.540 --> 00:29:00.370
supported by many collateral lines of
evidence is that the primary selective

00:29:00.370 --> 00:29:05.970
force for the evolution of lightly pink
bennet [SP] or more correctly, depigmented

00:29:05.970 --> 00:29:12.150
skin is promotion of ultraviolet
radiation-induced Vitamin D production in

00:29:12.150 --> 00:29:17.930
the skin under conditions of low and
seasonal ultraviolet radiation. And so

00:29:17.930 --> 00:29:24.200
here in modern humans, we have this
beautiful and delightful contrast between

00:29:24.200 --> 00:29:31.050
skin on the left that maximizes photo
protection against ultraviolet radiation,

00:29:31.050 --> 00:29:36.390
and skin on the right that maximizes
photosynthesis of Vitamin D under

00:29:36.390 --> 00:29:43.720
conditions of low UV. Skin pigmentation is
a superb evolutionary compromise.

00:29:43.720 --> 00:29:49.140
Something that we should talk about in our
classes of evolution and human biology; a

00:29:49.140 --> 00:29:54.670
superb compromise that is an excellent
illustration of the action of natural

00:29:54.670 --> 00:29:59.010
selection on the human body.
Themoregulation, I'm only going to say

00:29:59.010 --> 00:30:09.260
that as we evolved through time, we became
far more active. This beautiful example of

00:30:09.260 --> 00:30:15.340
an early member of the genus Homo was not
a tentative biped. This was a striding,

00:30:15.340 --> 00:30:22.680
running, active individual that built up a
lot of body heat under hot environmental

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:29.910
conditions. Here was the natural selective
substrate, as it were, for the loss of

00:30:29.910 --> 00:30:37.690
most functional body hair. Evaporation of
sweat is impeded by hair, and so we

00:30:37.690 --> 00:30:44.490
reasoned that most body...most functional
body hair was actually lost because of the

00:30:44.490 --> 00:30:51.170
importance of facilitating the evaporation
of sweat from the surface of the body. And

00:30:51.170 --> 00:30:57.330
so, functional hairlessness, then, can
best be thought about as facilitating

00:30:57.330 --> 00:31:03.200
active body cooling, whole body cooling,
through eccrine sweating during lengthy

00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:10.900
periods of sustained exercise.
Communication has always been an important

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:17.120
function of skin, whether we're talking
about a distant mammalian ancestor or a

00:31:17.120 --> 00:31:23.480
primate relative. Primates touch one
another. Communication through touch

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:30.470
especially beginning with infant-mother
communication is central. This continues,

00:31:30.470 --> 00:31:37.250
and is elaborated in the hairless human
infant and in hairless bodies contacting

00:31:37.250 --> 00:31:42.270
one another. And we know that this type of
touch communication is absolutely

00:31:42.270 --> 00:31:49.000
essential for mother-infant bonding in our
primate relatives and in ourselves. When

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:58.260
we lost most of our body hair, we lost an
important method of displaying our

00:31:58.260 --> 00:32:06.750
emotions. This chimpanzee on the left is
exhibiting a display, a very visible

00:32:06.750 --> 00:32:11.630
display, of anger and aggression toward
the individual on the right.

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:17.320
And he is able to manifest this
magnificent raising of hackles. What do we

00:32:17.320 --> 00:32:24.440
do without hair? We have no hackles. We
might...our little feeble hairs might go

00:32:24.440 --> 00:32:34.850
up. What do we do instead? We don't know
for certain, but what we do know is that

00:32:34.850 --> 00:32:41.300
modern humans have much more finely
differentiated, and highly active facial

00:32:41.300 --> 00:32:49.010
muscles than do even chimpanzees, and we
have the evolution of enhanced facial

00:32:49.010 --> 00:32:54.960
expressivity in humans that is probably
related to that loss of expressivity in

00:32:54.960 --> 00:33:02.250
the raising of the hackles. As soon as
humans evolved naked skin or probably very

00:33:02.250 --> 00:33:09.250
soon, thereafter, people realized that
they could decorate their skin. We don't

00:33:09.250 --> 00:33:15.570
know when they happened upon this, but we
have some enticing evidence that comes

00:33:15.570 --> 00:33:20.810
from Blombos Cave in South Africa from
about 70,000 years ago that would indicate

00:33:20.810 --> 00:33:27.130
that by that time, people were beginning
to use ocher for decorations and for

00:33:27.130 --> 00:33:34.780
decorating the inside of rock shelters.
This is exciting because I would venture

00:33:34.780 --> 00:33:41.110
that probably long before this, humans had
been using ocher and similar pigments to

00:33:41.110 --> 00:33:47.860
rub on themselves, to mark themselves. We
can't prove this, but it seems highly

00:33:47.860 --> 00:33:56.960
likely. Humans are lavish decorators of
themselves. We may not have colorful fur,

00:33:56.960 --> 00:34:04.410
but we more than compensate for this by
having myriad ways of decorating ourselves

00:34:04.410 --> 00:34:12.990
with body paint, with cosmetics.
In most cultures, both sexes are involved

00:34:12.990 --> 00:34:19.490
and many parts of the body are involved in
decoration. There is no culture that we

00:34:19.490 --> 00:34:28.460
know in the world that does not adorn its
skin in some way. Modern humans have

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:35.880
developed not only body paints but also
cosmetics. Now, mostly associated with

00:34:35.880 --> 00:34:41.610
women, but certainly centuries ago, not. A
lavish form of communication that is

00:34:41.610 --> 00:34:47.840
incredibly important that individuals can
manipulate and change from one day or one

00:34:47.840 --> 00:34:55.710
season to another. We also start making
permanent marks on our body. We know from

00:34:55.710 --> 00:35:02.880
the preserved remains of the so-called
Tyrolean iceman, dating from around 5,000

00:35:02.880 --> 00:35:08.850
years ago, that we have evidence of
tattooing of the skin. These are thought

00:35:08.850 --> 00:35:15.420
to be therapeutic tattoos that were on the
skin not necessarily decorative. Many of

00:35:15.420 --> 00:35:22.500
them are crosses or simple lines, parallel
lines. But the fact that they are present

00:35:22.500 --> 00:35:29.010
that early in the archaeological record in
neolithic humans is significant. And

00:35:29.010 --> 00:35:36.830
humans around the world tattoo themselves,
and sometimes lavishly. This woman from

00:35:36.830 --> 00:35:46.520
Burma has beautiful facial tattoos that
signify her marriageable status. And that

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:56.930
identify her to a particular clan group.
But what do we say just through our color?

00:35:56.930 --> 00:36:02.180
And the rest of this lecture I want to
devote to the messages, the communication

00:36:02.180 --> 00:36:10.160
that actually comes from our color.
During most of human history, humans moved

00:36:10.160 --> 00:36:18.380
around slowly. They came into contact with
one another gradually. There were no big

00:36:18.380 --> 00:36:26.380
surprises. And it's not surprising that
through much of history, not just

00:36:26.380 --> 00:36:33.050
prehistory but much of history, we have no
indication that humans treated one another

00:36:33.050 --> 00:36:40.910
differently on the basis of color. It only
is relatively recent, in the last few

00:36:40.910 --> 00:36:48.970
hundred years that color becomes something
that has social significance, and that has

00:36:48.970 --> 00:36:56.050
some kind of set of stereotypes and even
stigmas attached to it. We really see the

00:36:56.050 --> 00:37:05.160
emergence of a modern color-consciousness
beginning in the 18th century when innate

00:37:05.160 --> 00:37:14.090
skin color comes to communicate both
racial identity or race belonging, and

00:37:14.090 --> 00:37:21.880
social status. One of the most interesting
figures in this history is the philosopher

00:37:21.880 --> 00:37:29.960
Immanuel Kant. Immanuel Kant was a very
careful reader of Linnaeus, the great

00:37:29.960 --> 00:37:37.870
taxonomist. Linnaeus made very simple
descriptions of humans according to skin

00:37:37.870 --> 00:37:45.280
color and geography. Later, he associated
skin color and geography with some

00:37:45.280 --> 00:37:53.990
characteristics of behavior and culture.
Kant was an avid reader of Linnaeus, and

00:37:53.990 --> 00:38:01.740
Kant, although he's known far more for his
thoughts on rationality and human

00:38:01.740 --> 00:38:08.670
thinking, had tremendous curiosity about
human diversity, human origins, and the

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:12.080
origins of human capacity for
civilization.

00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:18.960
And so, he thought a lot about Linnaeus
and what Linnaeus said, and Kant, not a

00:38:18.960 --> 00:38:23.790
naturalist, but Immanuel Kant the
philosopher, was the first to actually

00:38:23.790 --> 00:38:31.670
enunciate the presence of four races. And
the key thing about Kant's races where

00:38:31.670 --> 00:38:38.060
that in his mind, they were immutable.
They couldn't change ever. And this was

00:38:38.060 --> 00:38:46.640
just not a list, it was a hierarchy. And
critical here is the primacy of the white

00:38:46.640 --> 00:38:53.160
race which is something that we see
emerging again in different guises for

00:38:53.160 --> 00:39:01.310
many centuries, for many decades after
this. Kant's tremendous influence was

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:09.360
complemented by the importance of
maintaining a strict social hierarchy in

00:39:09.360 --> 00:39:16.800
order to keep the trans-Atlantic slave
trade going. By the early 1800s, there was

00:39:16.800 --> 00:39:26.570
tremendous pressure to end slavery, to end
the slave trade. But it was very, very

00:39:26.570 --> 00:39:34.330
financially appealing and important for
the hierarchy of races and especially the

00:39:34.330 --> 00:39:40.580
primacy of the white race over the
so-called black race to be enunciated so

00:39:40.580 --> 00:39:46.500
that slavery could be maintained. And we
see this complementarity between a

00:39:46.500 --> 00:39:51.980
philosophical and a religious or
pseudo-religious underpinning for race

00:39:51.980 --> 00:39:58.580
hierarchies and slavery along with the
mercantile and capitalist underpinnings. A

00:39:58.580 --> 00:40:05.390
very pernicious system that led to the
social differentiation of color.

00:40:05.390 --> 00:40:12.490
Something that hadn't existed at least in
as strong a form and violent a form

00:40:12.490 --> 00:40:19.580
before. And so we see race definitions
that are associated with color that lead

00:40:19.580 --> 00:40:26.280
seemingly inexorably to the development of
racial stereotypes especially when they're

00:40:26.280 --> 00:40:33.410
propagated by individuals like Kant, like
Thomas Jefferson who were highly, socially

00:40:33.410 --> 00:40:38.220
influential through their writings leading
to the development of what I've called

00:40:38.220 --> 00:40:44.670
color memes that are adopted and
transmitted from family to family,

00:40:44.670 --> 00:40:51.370
generation to generation leading to a
durable psychosocial template for racism.

00:40:51.370 --> 00:40:59.970
So skin, coming from this delightful and
beautiful evolutionary background, skin

00:40:59.970 --> 00:41:07.680
color actually reflects our evolutionary
history, but in this most recent part of

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:16.910
human written history comes to represent
something entirely different. But I am not

00:41:16.910 --> 00:41:23.650
a pessimistic person, and the beautiful
thing about humans as primates is that we

00:41:23.650 --> 00:41:32.220
are tremendously imitative and suggestible
and we can change. We adopted in Western

00:41:32.220 --> 00:41:38.340
civilization broadly, certain attitudes
toward color and we can change those

00:41:38.340 --> 00:41:44.910
attitudes. We're not trapped by the color
memes that we have created. And this

00:41:44.910 --> 00:41:53.220
aspect of communication through skin can
in fact change. I want to celebrate the

00:41:53.220 --> 00:42:01.960
beauty of human skin and invite you to
think more about the exquisite path that

00:42:01.960 --> 00:42:08.670
skin has taken through the last seven or
so million years of the human lineage.

00:42:08.670 --> 00:42:16.050
The evolution of hairlessness, functional
nakedness, sweating, the development of

00:42:16.050 --> 00:42:23.660
these marvelous appendages, and the
beautiful feast of microbes and other

00:42:23.660 --> 00:42:29.890
creatures that live on the surface of our
skin. And then, the superb things that we

00:42:29.890 --> 00:42:36.500
do with this beautiful, naked canvass that
has been produced by evolution. Let's

00:42:36.500 --> 00:42:43.409
celebrate those and continue an active
program of research. Thank you very much.

00:42:47.514 --> 00:42:50.419
