00:43:34.680 --> 00:43:44.440
direct you to a traveling story. Skin is
our major defense against an onslaught of

00:43:44.440 --> 00:43:51.470
one of the strongest carcinogens that we
experience, ultraviolet light. And some

00:43:51.470 --> 00:43:55.820
years ago I was directed to this village
in Northern Guatemala were the

00:43:55.820 --> 00:44:00.430
missionary's orders that the children had
enormous amount of skin cancer, and they

00:44:00.430 --> 00:44:05.330
were dying at 10 years of age. Now,
commonly, you would think skin cancer as

00:44:05.330 --> 00:44:11.950
an older person's problem. These are
dramatic examples of how, if we lose the

00:44:11.950 --> 00:44:18.200
genetic defense against sun exposure,
cancer can be an enormously disastrous

00:44:18.200 --> 00:44:22.840
problem at the skin level. So they
directed me to this village and it had the

00:44:22.840 --> 00:44:29.110
phenotype of a disease that I'd work for
many years, xeroderma pigmentosum. That's

00:44:29.110 --> 00:44:34.920
normally a recessive disease. In then U.
S.population, it occurs about one to four

00:44:34.920 --> 00:44:39.500
per million of the population. Twenty-five
percent of the children had this disease.

00:44:39.500 --> 00:44:44.530
They lived under extreme poverty. When we
had a look at the patients, you could see

00:44:44.530 --> 00:44:51.890
the enormous sun damage of their face, and
the painful sunburns. When we brought

00:44:51.890 --> 00:44:58.120
cells back, you can see here and exposed
these cells to ultraviolet in the lab

00:44:58.120 --> 00:45:03.860
where the normal skin has excellent
survival, their cells were killed at very,

00:45:03.860 --> 00:45:09.140
very low doses of UV.
So they had a genetic predisposition in

00:45:09.140 --> 00:45:16.900
which they could not handle sun exposure,
solar exposure. We sequenced, and we found

00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:23.610
that they lacked what you call now the
global genome repair pathway. The founder

00:45:23.610 --> 00:45:29.530
effect in this village was a mutation
which caused...which removed one cytosine

00:45:29.530 --> 00:45:35.910
from a gene we call XPC which is one of
the main damage recognition proteins in

00:45:35.910 --> 00:45:42.830
the skin. When we did...even a staining of
a section of the skin, the black staining

00:45:42.830 --> 00:45:48.630
here, indications of high expression of
the XPC protein in the epidermis of normal

00:45:48.630 --> 00:45:54.050
skin. From the Guatemalan village, there
is no expression of this gene. As a

00:45:54.050 --> 00:45:59.360
result, their cells fail to recognize DNA
damage and it goes on to develop into

00:45:59.360 --> 00:46:06.550
cancer. I will show you some of the
ramifications of this. Now, xeroderma

00:46:06.550 --> 00:46:12.460
pigmentosum, XP, is one of a family of
some sensitive diseases involving

00:46:12.460 --> 00:46:18.190
different components of the nucleotide
excision repair pathway. As an aside, I'd

00:46:18.190 --> 00:46:24.690
just like to mention that you may have
seen that the Nobel prize for chemistry

00:46:24.690 --> 00:46:30.950
this year was given to Tom Lindahl, Z.
Sancar, and the mismatch repair pathway

00:46:30.950 --> 00:46:40.750
for unraveling the biochemistry of this
pathway. Now, xeroderma pigmentosum is

00:46:40.750 --> 00:46:47.790
unique from among the repair systems for
solar UV in that they have very high

00:46:47.790 --> 00:46:59.680
cancer. These other diseases are also
components of the same repair pathway, but

00:46:59.680 --> 00:47:04.080
they essentially are photosensitive but
without skin cancer.

00:47:04.080 --> 00:47:11.150
And especially a disease here known as the
UVS syndrome has acute sunburn, but no

00:47:11.150 --> 00:47:16.280
neurological disorders, none of the
developmental disorders or the current

00:47:16.280 --> 00:47:22.910
Cockayne syndrome, and a very mild
version. So there's an extremely wide

00:47:22.910 --> 00:47:28.630
variation in the genetic response to sun
exposure. Now the main photoproducts

00:47:28.630 --> 00:47:34.670
caused by UV occur between two adjacent
pyrimidines in the DNA. The major

00:47:34.670 --> 00:47:40.860
photoproduct is the dimer in which two
covalent bonds are formed. An alternative

00:47:40.860 --> 00:47:48.500
photoproduct, the 6-4 photoproduct. Now if
you do not remove these photoproducts,

00:47:48.500 --> 00:47:53.970
either of these, if you don't remove them
bio-chemically from the DNA, they can go

00:47:53.970 --> 00:48:00.500
on to interfere with DNA replication. And
a cytosine and a TC photoproduct can

00:48:00.500 --> 00:48:06.070
deaminate, code as an A, you know, codes
as a T and then opposite an A is placed.

00:48:06.070 --> 00:48:13.900
After two cycles of replication, a TC
sequence becomes a TT. So, a C to a T

00:48:13.900 --> 00:48:20.150
transition mutation in a TC sequence is an
absolute fingerprint for UV exposure and a

00:48:20.150 --> 00:48:27.390
UV-induced mutation. Now, the excision
repair pathway for UV damage has two major

00:48:27.390 --> 00:48:36.690
routes. If the DNA is unexpressed, which
is a large majority of our DNA, damage is

00:48:36.690 --> 00:48:41.520
recognized by a dedicated damage
recognition protein of which XPC, the

00:48:41.520 --> 00:48:47.600
Guatemalan population, has a mutation. So
they failed to recognize. An alternative

00:48:47.600 --> 00:48:53.760
mechanism by which damage is recognize is
an arrested transcription. If cells cannot

00:48:53.760 --> 00:48:58.270
recover from this, they have the disease
called Cockayne syndrome.

00:48:58.270 --> 00:49:03.150
And then, these two pathways converge on
an extensive remodeling system to repair

00:49:03.150 --> 00:49:07.720
the DNA. If we look more closely at the
transcription process, there are two

00:49:07.720 --> 00:49:12.000
strands, the coding strands and a template
strand. The template strand is the one

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:19.200
which is transcribed into RNA. The repair
of these two strands is different. The XPC

00:49:19.200 --> 00:49:24.350
system repairs this strand. The
transcribed strand is repaired by a

00:49:24.350 --> 00:49:28.270
complex of proteins that are associated
with a transcription complex. The

00:49:28.270 --> 00:49:33.900
difference between these two strands have
a major impact on carcinogenesis. First,

00:49:33.900 --> 00:49:38.910
if you look at repair in terms of the
removal of a number of photoproducts, with

00:49:38.910 --> 00:49:46.900
time, in a highly expressed gene like P53
or Dhfr, the photoproducts were remove

00:49:46.900 --> 00:49:52.170
rapidly. In unexpressed or lower expressed
genes, the photoproducts were removed to a

00:49:52.170 --> 00:49:57.700
much lower extent. So the rate of repair
depends upon which strand the damage lies.

00:49:57.700 --> 00:50:03.380
We then collaborated recently with a group
in Seattle, Laura Loeb and Kev Bayliss, in

00:50:03.380 --> 00:50:06.790
which they use a high throughput
sequencing method to determine exactly

00:50:06.790 --> 00:50:10.520
what are the sequence changes in a
UV-rated population. Now, those of

00:50:10.520 --> 00:50:14.530
you...those of us who have worked in a
million [sp] cell biology and tissue

00:50:14.530 --> 00:50:19.790
culture immunogenesis realize that over
the years, we've only had one or two genes

00:50:19.790 --> 00:50:25.100
that are capable of studying mutagenesis
in culture because of the number...the

00:50:25.100 --> 00:50:30.400
rarity of having a drug-selectable locus.
With high throughput sequencing, we can

00:50:30.400 --> 00:50:34.920
get by that completely. And so, here is
the result of measuring the mutation

00:50:34.920 --> 00:50:40.200
frequency in nucleotide changes per 10 to
the 7th nucleotides. High resolution

00:50:40.200 --> 00:50:45.120
sequencing averaged over a large number of
genes that are relevant for skin cancer.

00:50:45.120 --> 00:50:50.960
And you can see that a wild-type normal
cell has a low increase in mutations or

00:50:50.960 --> 00:50:58.850
function of dose, but in a XPC such as we
see in Guatemala village, enormous

00:50:58.850 --> 00:51:04.490
increase in mutation rates.
Going up from 0.5 up to 5, a tenfold or

00:51:04.490 --> 00:51:09.040
more increase in mutation rates. We then
decided once we had that system working,

00:51:09.040 --> 00:51:15.970
we went back to Guatemala and with some
help of a clinical service team that goes

00:51:15.970 --> 00:51:19.940
there from San Diego regularly to treat
the patients and give them some clinical

00:51:19.940 --> 00:51:27.350
help, we brought back five squamous
carcinomas from this population. Sequenced

00:51:27.350 --> 00:51:32.920
three million single nucleotide mutations
by exome sequencing. Transition mutations

00:51:32.920 --> 00:51:37.830
were a majority in XPC. Now since it was a
small population size, we didn't

00:51:37.830 --> 00:51:43.010
concentrate on which genes were mutated,
but we asked, "What is the frequency of

00:51:43.010 --> 00:51:47.520
mutations per kilobase across the whole
genome?" and asked, "What's the mutation

00:51:47.520 --> 00:51:53.730
density?" When we do that...this is a very
interesting situation to illustrate how

00:51:53.730 --> 00:52:00.250
the genome structure and function have a
major impact on mutation rates. In a

00:52:00.250 --> 00:52:04.500
normal population...see in here, normal
squamous carcinomas from a normal

00:52:04.500 --> 00:52:10.720
population. There is a protein in the
histone that methylates a region and

00:52:10.720 --> 00:52:18.120
suppresses access for other enzymes. As a
result, the mutation density goes up

00:52:18.120 --> 00:52:25.060
because those regions of the chromatin are
inaccessible to repair. As transcription

00:52:25.060 --> 00:52:31.950
increases across the genome, we find that
this is...removes the repression, and as a

00:52:31.950 --> 00:52:36.970
result mutation frequency declines. But
still, if you compare the non-transcribed

00:52:36.970 --> 00:52:41.580
strand to the transcribed strand in the
tumor, there are more mutations in the

00:52:41.580 --> 00:52:47.300
non-transcribed strand. When we move to
the XPC tumors from the Guatemalan

00:52:47.300 --> 00:52:55.450
patients, we find no removal on mutagenic
lesions right across the genome

00:52:55.450 --> 00:53:00.610
irrespective of transcription level, but
in the transcribed strand, very efficient

00:53:00.610 --> 00:53:03.520
removal.
Now these are striking illustrations of

00:53:03.520 --> 00:53:10.250
the fact that it depends critically which
strand of the DNA is damaged, which one

00:53:10.250 --> 00:53:16.800
gets repaired. If the cells fail to repair
the non-transcribed strand, mutation rate

00:53:16.800 --> 00:53:21.070
is very high when replication comes along
there. On the other strand, the

00:53:21.070 --> 00:53:26.660
transcribed strand, it doesn't matter how
well that's repaired in the Guatemalan

00:53:26.660 --> 00:53:32.200
population. Because they can't repair the
other strand, cancer is high. So that the

00:53:32.200 --> 00:53:37.690
repair of these transcribed strand could
be very efficient, but if confers

00:53:37.690 --> 00:53:43.290
absolutely no protection against
UV-induced mutations and carcinogenesis.

00:53:43.290 --> 00:53:50.120
Now, if we can turn to another response of
the skin to ultraviolet exposure, sunburn.

00:53:50.120 --> 00:53:57.830
We often think and it's established more
or less that the risk for melanoma from

00:53:57.830 --> 00:54:03.430
the sun is related to how many sunburns
you get. Well in squamous carcinoma

00:54:03.430 --> 00:54:08.520
there's a very different situation. This
is the spectrum of xeroderma pigmentosum

00:54:08.520 --> 00:54:12.520
patients from sun exposure, you can have a
patient with very high erythema and

00:54:12.520 --> 00:54:17.630
sunburn. You can have patients with
freckling. Patients that develop severe

00:54:17.630 --> 00:54:23.670
skin cancer. So you're going to have this
range, and this is under genetic control.

00:54:23.670 --> 00:54:28.070
If you look, and this is data published
recently from England where they

00:54:28.070 --> 00:54:33.170
have...bring in all the XPC patients from
the country, and treat them and follow

00:54:33.170 --> 00:54:38.420
them in one single location. And this was
reported a couple of years ago. If you

00:54:38.420 --> 00:54:47.470
look at sunburn versus which gene in the
XP repair pathway is mutated. If you look

00:54:47.470 --> 00:54:54.720
at the patients with mutations in XPC,
XPE, or XPV which are genes that code for

00:54:54.720 --> 00:55:01.490
proteins involved in the processing of DNA
damage in the non-expressed regions of the

00:55:01.490 --> 00:55:06.930
genome.
They get cancer but they get no sunburn.

00:55:06.930 --> 00:55:13.730
However, if the genes are involved in
repair and in transcription, sunburn is

00:55:13.730 --> 00:55:19.640
very high. If you now look at the
probability of cancer, and then look at

00:55:19.640 --> 00:55:26.450
patients that are involved...in which the
genes involved in transcription, cancer

00:55:26.450 --> 00:55:35.580
appears slowly over time. And the 50%
onset is out...almost out as late as the

00:55:35.580 --> 00:55:41.730
normal population. If we look at XPC and E
patients which are involved in the repair

00:55:41.730 --> 00:55:47.140
of the non-transcribed regions and they
don't get sunburn, the cancers are

00:55:47.140 --> 00:55:54.350
appearing more rapidly. Their 50% onset is
about the age of 20. So an acute sunburn

00:55:54.350 --> 00:56:00.740
in this disease is actually delays
squamous carcinoma. It's the converse of

00:56:00.740 --> 00:56:07.010
what you get with melanoma. As an aside,
it's interesting for me to note that the

00:56:07.010 --> 00:56:14.240
50% onset here is in the early 20s. In
American xeroderma patients, it occurs

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:20.210
below the age of 10 which is reminiscent
for my childhood that England is a pretty

00:56:20.210 --> 00:56:29.560
cloudy, damn rainy place. So let me just
summarize. Xeroderma pigmentosum and

00:56:29.560 --> 00:56:33.640
related nucleotide repair diseases
highlight mechanisms of sunburn and

00:56:33.640 --> 00:56:41.040
cancer. Repair is more rapid in more
highly expressed genes. Presumably because

00:56:41.040 --> 00:56:46.370
an expressed gene has to open up the
chromatin to allow transcription to work

00:56:46.370 --> 00:56:51.390
whereupon repair can work. Now deficient
repair of solar UV products in the

00:56:51.390 --> 00:56:56.150
non-transcribed strands, and in
unexpressed DNA results in a high mutation

00:56:56.150 --> 00:57:00.730
rate and cancer, but deficient repair in
the transcribed strand results in

00:57:00.730 --> 00:57:05.140
increased sunburn.
Cancer is delayed or not increased. And in

00:57:05.140 --> 00:57:09.680
fact, in Cockayne Syndrome, which is
uniquely involved in the repair of the

00:57:09.680 --> 00:57:14.590
transcribed strands, those patients with
Cockayne Syndrome have severe

00:57:14.590 --> 00:57:22.300
developmental disorders, but as far as we
know they never get cancer. So, my

00:57:22.300 --> 00:57:27.730
question that I leave you with is, "Can we
increase repair in otherwise healthy

00:57:27.730 --> 00:57:32.850
persons to protect against skin cancer
including melanoma and other cancers?" And

00:57:32.850 --> 00:57:38.280
alternatively, since the nucleotide
excision repair pathway repairs UV-type

00:57:38.280 --> 00:57:44.140
damage which is large modifications of DNA
very similar to what occurs when you use

00:57:44.140 --> 00:57:50.620
chemotherapy like cisplatins. Since it's
the same repair pathway, "Can we inhibit

00:57:50.620 --> 00:57:56.820
repair, and then sensitize cancers to
chemotherapy with very few side effects?"

00:57:56.820 --> 00:57:59.483
So I leave you with that. Thank you.

00:58:05.598 --> 00:58:08.600
♪ [music] ♪

